AB  - Purpose of reviewThis review discusses the urgency of addressing human-caused climate change and its impacts on health and the environment.The latest evidence shows that current climate changes are primarily attributable to greenhouse gas emissions from human industrial activity. Exceeding 1.5 degrees C of warming above preindustrial levels is projected to increase extreme weather events, increase rates of heat-related morbidity and mortality and vector-borne disease, exacerbate food and water insecurity, harm biodiversity and agriculture, displace communities, and disproportionately impact disadvantaged groups.Urgent action is required to curb emissions, enact adaptation strategies, and promote climate justice. The healthcare sector must reduce its ecological footprint and prepare systems and workers to address climate change's health effects. Further research should support climate solutions while promoting health equity and environmental justice.Papers of particular interest, published within the annual period of review, have been highlighted as:In the mid-1880 s, scientists initiated the systematic tracking of temperature measurements worldwide, initially through weather stations and ships, and later with the aid of satellites [1]. As this comprehensive collection of data expanded, a discernible pattern emerged: over the past 150 years, the average global temperature has exhibited a persistent upward trend, with the rate of warming progressively intensifying [2]. This wealth of data became the foundation of the burgeoning field of climate science, providing compelling evidence that the planet is undergoing an unparalleled era of rapid warming, primarily attributable to human activities (i.e., anthropogenic influence). The term "global warming" encapsulates this trend of rising global temperatures, although the term "climate change" is now more frequently used, as it also encompasses the multifaceted and diverse impacts resulting from the escalation in global temperatures [3].The mean global surface temperature is estimated to have increased by 1.09 degrees C (1.8 degrees F) during the period from 2010 to 2019 compared to the period from 1850 to 1900 [2]. Moreover, the rate of temperature rise has been notably faster since 1970 than at any point in the past 2000 years [2]. This accelerated warming trend has led to a surge in the frequency and intensity of heat waves, and it has also triggered a cascade of impacts resulting from rising global temperatures. Consequently, our oceans are experiencing warming and increased acidity, ice caps are melting, sea levels are rising, and precipitation patterns are undergoing significant changes, leading to both more frequent flooding and prolonged droughts [4]. Much of the climate science to date is regularly assessed and consolidated by the Intergovernmental Panel on Climate Change (IPCC). The IPCC was first assembled in 1988 by the United Nations (UN) in order to monitor and assess science related to climate change [5]. Participation is open to all member countries of the UN. The IPCC regularly releases reports generated by scientists who volunteer their time and expertise to review and assess published literature on climate science. These reports provide a scientific basis for governments to develop climate-related policies. The most recent report was the 6th Synthesis report released in March 2023 [6].The science summarized by the IPCC reports has established several important facts that shape both our understanding of and our response to climate change [6].
   First, the current era of climate change is a direct result of human activity [7]. Second, the risks of climate change greatly increase once the globe has warmed more than 1.5 C from preindustrial levels, a milestone that is rapidly approaching [8]. Third, significant changes must occur in human activity to reverse warming trends and mitigate risks [8]. no caption availableAlthough the current era of climate change is unprecedented in multiple ways, it is also true that, throughout Earth's history, there have been periods of global temperature shifts that have had large-scale impacts on the Earth's life forms. In the past, these temperature shifts were primarily driven by natural forces in the form of solar energy, ocean circulation, and volcanic activity [9]. However, repeated modeling by scientists has shown that the intense warming that has occurred over the past century cannot be due to these natural drivers alone. In fact, solar output has actually declined since 1880 and volcanic activity has exerted primarily a cooling effect [10]. At most, natural drivers have increased the global temperature by 0.1 degrees C, while some estimates suggest that natural drivers have overall decreased the global temperature by 0.1 degrees C since the 1880 s [10].Modeling has shown that the only explanation for the drastic warming of the last century is human activity, primarily via the generation of greenhouse gases (GHGs) [10]. GHGs are gases that trap heat in the atmosphere by absorbing light and preventing it from escaping the Earth. The main GHGs contributing to climate change are carbon dioxide, methane, nitrous oxide, and fluorinated gases [2]. In 2019, atmospheric CO2 concentrations were higher than any other time in the last 2 million years and concentrations of methane and nitrous oxide were higher than at any time in the last 800 000 years [2]. The odds of current warming occurring without anthropogenic greenhouse gas emissions is less than 1 in 100 000 [11].The majority of these GHGs come from industrial activities. In 2019, approximately 79% of global GHG emissions came from sectors of energy, industry, transport, and buildings together while 22% came from agriculture, forestry, and other land use [2]. Specifically, carbon dioxide is primarily released via fossil fuel combustion and industrial processes, while methane and nitrous oxide are primarily released from agricultural activities [2].The recent IPCC reports have unambiguously conveyed that when the global mean surface temperature (GMST) reaches 1.5 degrees C (2.7 degrees F) above preindustrial temperatures (with a reference period of 1850-1900 approximating preindustrial temperature), the climate-related risks to both human and natural systems greatly increase [6]. Based on these reports, the countries who participated in the 2015 Paris Agreement agreed to limit warming to 1.5 degrees C--2 degrees C by 2030 in order to mitigate the worst effects of climate change [12]. Currently, the GMST is estimated to be 1.08 degrees C above preindustrial levels and is predicted to reach 1.5 degrees C increase between 2030 and 2052 if human GHG emissions remain steady and earlier if GHG emissions continue to grow at their current rates [13].Although future climate-related risks are greater if warming exceeds 1.5 degrees C, the level of risk to human and natural systems is dependent on the degree of warming. The impacts of climate change will be increasingly severe the more that the GMST rises above 1.5 degrees C preindustrial levels [13]. Although the Paris Agreement aims to limit the warming to 1.
   5 degrees C-2 degrees C, there are worst-case scenarios projected by certain models, depicting a potential increase of up to 5 degrees C (9 degrees F) by the year 2100 [14]. Additionally, although we have not yet hit a 1.5 degrees C increase, we are already seeing downstream effects related to warming: ice caps are melting, sea levels are rising, and oceans are warming and becoming more acidic [2].The impacts associated with 1.5 degrees C warming are geographically diverse, with varying consequences across the globe. According to the IPCC, a substantial 3.3-3.6 billion people currently reside in areas that are highly vulnerable to climate change [15]. Greater frequency of heat waves and droughts in many parts of the globe (particularly the Middle East and South Asia) are predicted to significantly increase the number of annual days where it is too hot for humans to go outside without significant risk to health and life [15]. Other weather-related changes that are predicted to occur in various parts of the globe include increases in aridity and fire weather in some regions and increased rainfall and extreme flooding in others, intensification of tropical cyclones and/or extratropical storms, and threatening of coastal areas by sea level rise [15].Extreme weather events are likely to have a direct impact on human lives and health, including increased morbidity and mortality from heat waves and deaths related to storms and fire weather. Other predicted associations between climate change and human health include an increased spread of vector-borne diseases such as malaria and dengue fever, increased trauma from extreme weather events, and an increase in mental health conditions and interpersonal violence associated with extreme weather [16].In addition to the direct impacts of extreme weather events on human lives, a 1.5 degrees C warming will likely have downstream influences on human health via its effects on food and water security. Already, climate change has slowed agricultural productivity in many parts of the globe over the last 50 years [17]. Ocean warming and acidification have caused loss of both oceanic and freshwater species and adversely impacted food production from fisheries and shellfish aquaculture. Roughly half of the world's population already experiences severe water scarcity for at least part of the year, and this will only increase as temperature warms [18].The IPCC report also predicts the effects of a 1.5 degrees C rise on human livelihoods, homes, and well being. Climate and weather extremes are increasingly driving displacement in almost all parts of the globe, with small island states in the Caribbean and Pacific being disproportionately affected. The number of "climate migrants" will likely continue to rise, as homes and food and water security are threatened [16]. Additionally, economic damages from climate change have already been recorded in industries such as agriculture, forestry, fisheries, energy, and tourism, which may further drive the displacement of communities, as they lose access to traditional livelihoods and culture [16].Although the specific impacts of climate change will vary regionally, the common theme of the effects of climate change on human health and well being is that existing inequalities will be made worse. Disadvantaged and vulnerable populations, indigenous communities, and local communities dependent on agricultural or coastal livelihoods are at a disproportionate risk of experiencing adverse effects with a 1.5 degrees C increase in temperature.
   The Global Climate Risk Index shows that many lower income countries are at the highest risk of extreme weather events [19]. Already, data show that between 1961 and 2000, climate change harmed the economies of the poorest countries while boosting economies of wealthier nations, increasing the global wealth gap by 25% [20].To limit warming to 1.5 degrees C by 2030, most models suggest that, by 2030, global CO2 emissions must decline by 45% from 2010 levels and then must approach net-zero emissions by 2050 [6]. Solar energy, wind energy, electrification of urban systems, urban green infrastructure, energy efficiency demand-side management, improved forest and grassland management, and reduced food waste and loss are all existing, technically viable, and cost-effective methods for reducing greenhouse gas emissions [21-25].However, achieving the 1.5 degrees C target requires more than these mitigation efforts alone. Rapid transitions in energy, land, urban and infrastructure, and industrial systems are essential. Additionally, carbon dioxide removal (CDR) on a substantial scale ranging from 100 to 1000 GTCO2 (gigatons of carbon dioxide) will be necessary [26]. Existing CDR methods include afforestation and reforestation, land restoration and soil carbon sequestration, bioenergy with carbon capture and storage (BECCS), direct air carbon capture and storage (DACCS), and enhanced weathering and ocean alkalinization [8].Despite the existing methods for reducing GHGs and for CDR, the nationally determined contributions to greenhouse gas emissions that have been announced as of October 2021 make it more likely than not that warming will exceed 1.5 degrees C during the 21st century and will make it harder to limit warming below 2 degrees C [8]. If this were the case, greater CDR utilization would be required to sustain net negative carbon emissions and lower global mean surface temperature.Technological solutions are an essential but insufficient component of the response to climate change. Any efforts to address climate change must consider existing social and economic inequities and the potential for worsening these inequities. Technological solutions that seek to address the impacts of climate change should be assessed and implemented within a sustainable development framework, which the United Nations defines as "development that meets the needs of the present without compromising the ability of future generations to meet their own needs" [27]. The feasibility of the United Nations sustainable development model is predicated on the idea that developed countries who have signed the United Nations Framework Convention on Climate Change should mobilize funds to address the climate mitigation and adaptation needs of countries that are still developing. This obligation arises from the fact that approximately 70% of global greenhouse gas emissions comes from China, the United States, the EU, India, Russia, and Japan, while most of the countries who are experiencing the worst effects of climate change have comparatively negligible greenhouse gas emissions [28].Ultimately, addressing climate change in a sustainable and equitable way will require a multifaceted approach that considers local sociopolitical contexts, resources, and needs. The response to climate change thus far has been insufficient and the chances for keeping global warming below 1.5 degrees C continue to grow increasingly slim. In order to limit further warming, fossil fuels must be completely phased out and large-scale changes must be made to agriculture and forestry.
   On its surface, climate change may not seemingly be connected to healthcare. As outlined in this review, however, climate change is already having detrimental effects on human health which will only continue to worsen if warming is left unchecked. The growing field of planetary health seeks to understand and address the impacts of human disruptions to Earth's natural systems on human health and offers a framework for how clinicians can conceptualize the link between climate change and health [29]. As outlined in the IPCC summary, climate change and its sequelae increase the frequency and range of vector-borne infectious disease, leave people more susceptible to malnutrition and disease via the effects of extreme weather and drought on agriculture and biodiversity, increase the health risks of air pollution from wildfires and/or industrial emissions, and pose direct threats to human lives via extreme weather. Healthcare workers will continue to confront the health effects of climate change among their patients and communities and should be informed about climate change in order to better treat and advocate for their patients. Incorporating concepts of planetary health into medical curriculum will ensure that future physicians are better equipped to address the health implications of climate change. An example of the impact of climate change on kidney health in particular is the impact of a warming planet on fetal development, particularly lower nephron endowment, which increases the risk of hypertension and chronic kidney disease later in life [30].In addition to understanding the health implications of climate change, healthcare workers should also be aware of the ways in which the health sector contributes to climate change. The healthcare sector is responsible for approximately 10% of greenhouse gas emissions, with hospitals accounting for a third of emissions [31]. Hospitals use 2.5 times more energy per square foot than an office building and spend more than $6.5 billion on energy each year [31]. Healthcare administrators and employees are in a prime position to advocate for hospitals to transition away from fossil fuels and towards clean, renewable energy sources. Not only would this improve downstream effects on patients' health, but it would also result in an estimated $1.2 billion reduction in medical costs [32]. Additionally, hospitals can make significant reductions in their greenhouse gas emissions through reduction of waste, shifting towards sustainable procurement methods, adopting more plant-based foods in hospital cafeterias and investing in sustainable food waste programs, and investment in community resilience against climate change. The Healthcare Climate Council's Climate Action "Playbook for Hospitals" offers tangible steps that many hospital systems have already taken and that others can adopt to reduce greenhouse gas emissions [33].Although many of the health effects of climate change are already known, much more research is needed on the ways in which warmer temperatures and extreme weather events will impact health. More research is also needed on the ways in which healthcare workers can best educate and advocate for their patients in the context of climate change. The healthcare sector has a role to play in combating climate change and understanding the fundamentals of climate science is an essential foundation.None.Purpose of reviewThis review discusses the urgency of addressing human-caused climate change and its impacts on health and the environment.
