s are in a prime position to advocate for hospitals to transition away from fossil fuels and towards clean, renewable energy sources. Not only would this improve downstream effects on patients' health, but it would also result in an estimated $1.2 billion reduction in medical costs [32]. Additionally, hospitals can make significant reductions in their greenhouse gas emissions through reduction of waste, shifting towards sustainable procurement methods, adopting more plant-based foods in hospital cafeterias and investing in sustainable food waste programs, and investment in community resilience against climate change. The Healthcare Climate Council's Climate Action "Playbook for Hospitals" offers tangible steps that many hospital systems have already taken and that others can adopt to reduce greenhouse gas emissions [33].Although many of the health effects of climate change are already known, much more research is needed on the ways in which warmer temperatures and extreme weather events will impact health. More research is also needed on the ways in which healthcare workers can best educate and advocate for their patients in the context of climate change. The healthcare sector has a role to play in combating climate change and understanding the fundamentals of climate science is an essential foundation.None.Purpose of reviewThis review discusses the urgency of addressing human-caused climate change and its impacts on health and the environment.
