sheries and shellfish aquaculture. Roughly half of the world's population already experiences severe water scarcity for at least part of the year, and this will only increase as temperature warms [18].The IPCC report also predicts the effects of a 1.5 degrees C rise on human livelihoods, homes, and well being. Climate and weather extremes are increasingly driving displacement in almost all parts of the globe, with small island states in the Caribbean and Pacific being disproportionately affected. The number of "climate migrants" will likely continue to rise, as homes and food and water security are threatened [16]. Additionally, economic damages from climate change have already been recorded in industries such as agriculture, forestry, fisheries, energy, and tourism, which may further drive the displacement of communities, as they lose access to traditional livelihoods and culture [16].Although the specific impacts of climate change will vary regionally, the common theme of the effects of climate change on human health and well being is that existing inequalities will be made worse. Disadvantaged and vulnerable populations, indigenous communities, and local communities dependent on agricultural or coastal livelihoods are at a disproportionate risk of experiencing adverse effects with a 1.5 degrees C increase in temperature. The Global Climate Risk Index shows that many lower income countries are at the highest risk of extreme weather events [19].
