ial for worsening these inequities. Technological solutions that seek to address the impacts of climate change should be assessed and implemented within a sustainable development framework, which the United Nations defines as "development that meets the needs of the present without compromising the ability of future generations to meet their own needs" [27]. The feasibility of the United Nations sustainable development model is predicated on the idea that developed countries who have signed the United Nations Framework Convention on Climate Change should mobilize funds to address the climate mitigation and adaptation needs of countries that are still developing. This obligation arises from the fact that approximately 70% of global greenhouse gas emissions comes from China, the United States, the EU, India, Russia, and Japan, while most of the countries who are experiencing the worst effects of climate change have comparatively negligible greenhouse gas emissions [28].Ultimately, addressing climate change in a sustainable and equitable way will require a multifaceted approach that considers local sociopolitical contexts, resources, and needs. The response to climate change thus far has been insufficient and the chances for keeping global warming below 1.5 degrees C continue to grow increasingly slim. In order to limit further warming, fossil fuels must be completely phased out and large-scale changes must be made to agriculture and forestry.On its surface, climate change may not seemingly be connected to healthcare.
