m 2010 to 2019 compared to the period from 1850 to 1900 [2]. Moreover, the rate of temperature rise has been notably faster since 1970 than at any point in the past 2000 years [2]. This accelerated warming trend has led to a surge in the frequency and intensity of heat waves, and it has also triggered a cascade of impacts resulting from rising global temperatures. Consequently, our oceans are experiencing warming and increased acidity, ice caps are melting, sea levels are rising, and precipitation patterns are undergoing significant changes, leading to both more frequent flooding and prolonged droughts [4]. Much of the climate science to date is regularly assessed and consolidated by the Intergovernmental Panel on Climate Change (IPCC). The IPCC was first assembled in 1988 by the United Nations (UN) in order to monitor and assess science related to climate change [5]. Participation is open to all member countries of the UN. The IPCC regularly releases reports generated by scientists who volunteer their time and expertise to review and assess published literature on climate science. These reports provide a scientific basis for governments to develop climate-related policies. The most recent report was the 6th Synthesis report released in March 2023 [6].The science summarized by the IPCC reports has established several important facts that shape both our understanding of and our response to climate change [6]. First, the current era of climate change is a direct result of human activity [7]. Second, the risks of climate change greatly increase once the globe has warmed more than 1.
