her while 22% came from agriculture, forestry, and other land use [2]. Specifically, carbon dioxide is primarily released via fossil fuel combustion and industrial processes, while methane and nitrous oxide are primarily released from agricultural activities [2].The recent IPCC reports have unambiguously conveyed that when the global mean surface temperature (GMST) reaches 1.5 degrees C (2.7 degrees F) above preindustrial temperatures (with a reference period of 1850-1900 approximating preindustrial temperature), the climate-related risks to both human and natural systems greatly increase [6]. Based on these reports, the countries who participated in the 2015 Paris Agreement agreed to limit warming to 1.5 degrees C--2 degrees C by 2030 in order to mitigate the worst effects of climate change [12]. Currently, the GMST is estimated to be 1.08 degrees C above preindustrial levels and is predicted to reach 1.5 degrees C increase between 2030 and 2052 if human GHG emissions remain steady and earlier if GHG emissions continue to grow at their current rates [13].Although future climate-related risks are greater if warming exceeds 1.5 degrees C, the level of risk to human and natural systems is dependent on the degree of warming. The impacts of climate change will be increasingly severe the more that the GMST rises above 1.5 degrees C preindustrial levels [13]. Although the Paris Agreement aims to limit the warming to 1.5 degrees C-2 degrees C, there are worst-case scenarios projected by certain models, depicting a potential increase of up to 5 degrees C (9 degrees F) by the year 2100 [14]. Additionally, although we have not yet hit a 1.
